4. MEMORY ARCHITECTURE: QUANTUM-SYNAPTIC UNIFICATION

4.1 Holographic Quantum-Synaptic Memory

Physical Implementation:

· Photonic crystals with quantum dots for dense storage
· Atomic vapor cells for both quantum state and analog weight storage
· Surface acoustic wave devices for temporal pattern storage

Access Mechanisms:

```
READ: |address⟩ → [Quantum Fourier Transform] → [Pattern Interference] → |data⟩
WRITE: |data⟩ ⊗ |address⟩ → [Interference Pattern] → [Material Response]
ERASE: Apply orthogonal pattern to destructively interfere
```

4.2 Memory Hierarchy Details

```
LEVEL 0: Qubit registers (100s of qubits, ~100μs coherence)
LEVEL 1: Quantum cache (1000s of qubits, error-corrected)
LEVEL 2: Synaptic SRAM (Analog, non-volatile, 10ns access)
LEVEL 3: Holographic main memory (PB scale, 100ns access)
LEVEL 4: Photonic archival storage (EB scale, ms access)
```

4.3 Coherence Protocols Extended

Quantum-Synaptic Consistency:

· When a quantum weight is measured (collapsed), update all synaptic copies
· When synapses undergo plasticity, adjust quantum amplitudes proportionally
· Use "consensus algorithms" for distributed weight updates

